      <scopecontent id="aspace_c884e292298f207e35a07a8a93f3decf">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The Walter W. and Lillian F. Norton Papers consist of materials relating to the World War I Liberty Loan, to the genealogy of the Norton family, and to stamp collecting. Included are correspondence, printed matter, receipts, and other papers.</p>
         <p>The papers of Lillian Frances (Reynolds) Norton deal with her work as chairwoman of the Liberty Loan Committee of Lakeville, Connecticut, between 1917 and 1919. In her correspondence are circular letters, memoranda, printed forms, receipts, and other items from the Connecticut State Council of Defense, the Treasury Department, the National Woman's Liberty Loan Committee, and the Liberty Loan Committee of New England. There are, in addition, pamphlets, leaflets, newsletters, bulletins, manuals for loan salespeople, and a miscellany of other printed matter, certificates, and related materials.</p>
         <p>The papers of Walter Whittlesey Norton (1867-1924), husband of Lillian F. Norton, fall into two parts. The first consists of a bound manuscript genealogical record of the descendants of John Norton and Jane Cooper, compiled between 1898 and 1924, accompanied by several items of correspondence and other papers. The remainder of Walter Norton's papers are letters, mainly from the nineteen-teens and nineteen-twenties, concerned with his stamp collection. Some printed matter and receipts are interfiled with the letters, which are arranged alphabetically by correspondent.</p>
         <p>The Norton genealogy was given to Yale University by the Collector's Shop in 1943; the rest of the papers were separated from the Holley Manufacturing Company Papers (Ms. Gr. No. 286), which were purchased for Yale in 1946. The latter collection was transferred to the University of Connecticut in 1980.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
